#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:3
msgid "Advanced F2PY use cases"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:6
msgid "Adding user-defined functions to F2PY generated modules"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:8
msgid ""
"User-defined Python C/API functions can be defined inside signature files "
"using ``usercode`` and ``pymethoddef`` statements (they must be used inside "
"the ``python module`` block). For example, the following signature file "
"``spam.pyf``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:1
msgid ""
"!    -*- f90 -*-\n"
"python module spam\n"
"    usercode '''\n"
"  static char doc_spam_system[] = \"Execute a shell command.\";\n"
"  static PyObject *spam_system(PyObject *self, PyObject *args)\n"
"  {\n"
"    char *command;\n"
"    int sts;\n"
"\n"
"    if (!PyArg_ParseTuple(args, \"s\", &command))\n"
"        return NULL;\n"
"    sts = system(command);\n"
"    return Py_BuildValue(\"i\", sts);\n"
"  }\n"
"    '''\n"
"    pymethoddef '''\n"
"    {\"system\",  spam_system, METH_VARARGS, doc_spam_system},\n"
"    '''\n"
"end python module spam\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:16
msgid "wraps the C library function ``system()``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:18
msgid "f2py -c spam.pyf"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:20
msgid "In Python this can then be used as:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:22
msgid ""
">>> import spam\n"
">>> status = spam.system('whoami')\n"
"pearu\n"
">>> status = spam.system('blah')\n"
"sh: line 1: blah: command not found"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:26
msgid "Adding user-defined variables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:28
msgid ""
"The following example illustrates how to add user-defined variables to a "
"F2PY generated extension module by modifying the dictionary of a F2PY "
"generated module. Consider the following signature file (compiled with "
"``f2py -c var.pyf``):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:32
msgid ""
"!    -*- f90 -*-\n"
"python module var\n"
"  usercode '''\n"
"    int BAR = 5;\n"
"  '''\n"
"  interface\n"
"    usercode '''\n"
"      PyDict_SetItemString(d,\"BAR\",PyLong_FromLong(BAR));\n"
"    '''\n"
"  end interface\n"
"end python module\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:35
msgid ""
"Notice that the second ``usercode`` statement must be defined inside an "
"``interface`` block and the module dictionary is available through the "
"variable ``d`` (see ``varmodule.c`` generated by ``f2py var.pyf`` for "
"additional details)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:40
msgid "Usage in Python:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:42
msgid ""
">>> import var\n"
">>> var.BAR\n"
"5"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:47
msgid "Dealing with KIND specifiers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:49
msgid ""
"Currently, F2PY can handle only ``<type spec>(kind=<kindselector>)`` "
"declarations where ``<kindselector>`` is a numeric integer (e.g. 1, 2, "
"4,...), but not a function call ``KIND(..)`` or any other expression. F2PY "
"needs to know what would be the corresponding C type and a general solution "
"for that would be too complicated to implement."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:55
msgid ""
"However, F2PY provides a hook to overcome this difficulty, namely, users can "
"define their own <Fortran type> to <C type> maps. For example, if Fortran 90 "
"code contains::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:59
msgid "REAL(kind=KIND(0.0D0)) ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:61
msgid "then create a mapping file containing a Python dictionary::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:63
msgid "{'real': {'KIND(0.0D0)': 'double'}}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:65
msgid "for instance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:67
msgid ""
"Use the ``--f2cmap`` command-line option to pass the file name to F2PY. By "
"default, F2PY assumes file name is ``.f2py_f2cmap`` in the current working "
"directory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:71
msgid "More generally, the f2cmap file must contain a dictionary with items::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:74
msgid "<Fortran typespec> : {<selector_expr>:<C type>}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:76
msgid "that defines mapping between Fortran type::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:78
msgid "<Fortran typespec>([kind=]<selector_expr>)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:80
msgid ""
"and the corresponding <C type>. The <C type> can be one of the following::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:82
msgid ""
"double\n"
"float\n"
"long_double\n"
"char\n"
"signed_char\n"
"unsigned_char\n"
"short\n"
"unsigned_short\n"
"int\n"
"long\n"
"long_long\n"
"unsigned\n"
"complex_float\n"
"complex_double\n"
"complex_long_double\n"
"string"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:99
msgid "For example, for a Fortran file ``func1.f`` containing:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:101
msgid ""
"      subroutine func1(n, x, res)\n"
"        use, intrinsic :: iso_fortran_env, only: int64, real64\n"
"        implicit none\n"
"        integer(int64), intent(in) :: n\n"
"        real(real64), intent(in) :: x(n)\n"
"        real(real64), intent(out) :: res\n"
"Cf2py   intent(hide) :: n\n"
"        res = sum(x)\n"
"      end\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:104
msgid ""
"In order to convert ``int64`` and ``real64`` to valid ``C`` data types, a ``."
"f2py_f2cmap`` file with the following content can be created in the current "
"directory:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:107
msgid "dict(real=dict(real64='double'), integer=dict(int64='long long'))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:111
msgid ""
"and create the module as usual. F2PY checks if a ``.f2py_f2cmap`` file is "
"present in the current directory and will use it to map ``KIND`` specifiers "
"to ``C`` data types."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:114
msgid "f2py -c func1.f -m func1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:118
msgid ""
"Alternatively, the mapping file can be saved with any other name, for "
"example ``mapfile.txt``, and this information can be passed to F2PY by using "
"the ``--f2cmap`` option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:121
msgid "f2py -c func1.f -m func1 --f2cmap mapfile.txt"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:125
msgid "For more information, see F2Py source code ``numpy/f2py/capi_maps.py``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:130
msgid "Character strings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:133
msgid "Assumed length character strings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:135
msgid ""
"In Fortran, assumed length character string arguments are declared as "
"``character*(*)`` or ``character(len=*)``, that is, the length of such "
"arguments are determined by the actual string arguments at runtime. For "
"``intent(in)`` arguments, this lack of length information poses no problems "
"for f2py to construct functional wrapper functions. However, for "
"``intent(out)`` arguments, the lack of length information is problematic for "
"f2py generated wrappers because there is no size information available for "
"creating memory buffers for such arguments and F2PY assumes the length is "
"0.  Depending on how the length of assumed length character strings are "
"specified, there exist ways to workaround this problem, as exemplified below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:147
msgid ""
"If the length of the ``character*(*)`` output argument is determined by the "
"state of other input arguments, the required connection can be established "
"in a signature file or within a f2py-comment by adding an extra declaration "
"for the corresponding argument that specifies the length in character "
"selector part. For example, consider a Fortran file ``asterisk1.f90``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:1
msgid ""
"subroutine foo1(s)\n"
"  character*(*), intent(out) :: s\n"
"  !f2py character(f2py_len=12) s\n"
"  s = \"123456789A12\"\n"
"end subroutine foo1\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:157
msgid ""
"Compile it with ``f2py -c asterisk1.f90 -m asterisk1`` and then in Python:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:1
msgid ""
">>> import asterisk1\n"
">>> asterisk1.foo1()\n"
"b'123456789A12'\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:162
msgid ""
"Notice that the extra declaration ``character(f2py_len=12) s`` is "
"interpreted only by f2py and in the ``f2py_len=`` specification one can use "
"C-expressions as a length value."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:166
msgid "In the following example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:1
msgid ""
"subroutine foo2(s, n)\n"
"  character(len=*), intent(out) :: s\n"
"  integer, intent(in) :: n\n"
"  !f2py character(f2py_len=n), depend(n) :: s\n"
"  s = \"123456789A123456789B\"(1:n)\n"
"end subroutine foo2\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:171
msgid ""
"the length of the output assumed length string depends on an input argument "
"``n``, after wrapping with F2PY, in Python:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/advanced/use_cases.rst:1
msgid ""
">>> import asterisk\n"
">>> asterisk.foo2(2)\n"
"b'12'\n"
">>> asterisk.foo2(12)\n"
"b'123456789A12'\n"
">>> \n"
msgstr ""
